        OCEAN is a multi-user game written by Chris Caldwell
with considerable input from Roger Long and some Macro-10
assembly coding by Robert Kenney at the University of New Hampshire.  

To run the game under Tops10, type in:

        .R GAM:OCEAN -switch /switch /switch . . .

where "switch" may be any of the following options:

  A terminal type:
    ADDS580         for use on ADDS580 terminals
    ADM3A           for use on ADM3A terminals
    VT52            for use on DEC scopes
    ISC             for use on the ISC graphic terminal
    ISCBIG          for use with A7 mode on the ISC graphics terminal
    PE550           for use on PERKINS ELMER terminals
    ADDS980         for use on ADDS980 terminals
    ACTV            for use on ACT-V terminals
    ADVANT          for use with North Star ADVANTage terminals
    ANSI            for use on any ANSI terminal (now with color!)
                    When in doubt, use ANSI.

  A ship type:
    BATTLE	    User wishes to operate a BATTLESHIP
    SUBMAR	    User wishes to operate a SUBMARINE
    DESTRO	    User wishes to operate a DESTROYER
    PT	            User wishes to operate a P.T. BOAT
    HELICO	    User wishes to operate a HELICOPTER

  Or:
    OLDANG          use 0"=East, 90"=North, 180"=West, 270"=South
  		    Otherwise 0"=North, 90"=East, 180"=South, 270"=West

If you don't specify a terminal type, you will be prompted for one.
If you don't specify /OLDANG, the normal compass rose of 0"-means-
North will be used instead of the old (incorrect) 0"-means-East
system.  If the user doesn't specify his type of ship, then
the program will randomly chose one.

The first large box contains the radar.  The radar represents
an over view of with a range of 10 sectors on either side.

Characters seen in the radar:

	#		Represents land
	-		Represents ground below water (submarine)
	.		Bubble caused by ship moving underwater
			when speed is 10 or better.
	+		Mine
	<LETTER>	Represents a ship
	<SPACE>		Indicates that the radar cannot
			detect the bottom


The second box contains the sonar which is a cross section of
the ocean taken at the scan bearing.  The scan bearing defaults
to the current azimuth.

The damage is displayed on the bottom.

	O	-	Operational
	P	-	Cannot be repaired unless at a port
	<NUMBER>-	Number of quarter minutes until repaired

